metadata.name: Vents #388
metadata.description:
Near the start of December @Studio Yorktown launched his "Studio Yorktown Color Town Hall" library of wonderful colour palettes.

"You know what this Town Hall needs?" I asked no one in particular, "Vents!". Besides, what's more Christmassy than a good old vent?

Some nice soothing gradients, with a selection of innies and outies, structure, form, and sometimes sharp edges. I humbly suggest aiming to get a set of three üòÅ

Thank you for everything fxhash in 2022, looking forwards to 2023!

metadata.name: Platonics #25
metadata.description:
A response to being buffeted by forces outside of our control. Platonics sought to find order, control and solace in the Platonic solids. Instead it found beauty and intrigue in the emergent chaos that can arise from even the simplest systems.

Its building blocks are the five Platonic solids. Forms which have fascinated humanity for thousands of years. Their title comes from the philosophy of Plato, who equated each of the solids with a classical element.

Platonics arranges these forms in a series of geometric layouts, with varying density and randomness. At one extreme we see tidy radial circles consisting of a single solid. At the other, packed pentagons consisting of jumbled solids give rise to Escher-esque compositions which hold near infinite variety, variety enhanced by a range of pens and colours that draw and fill those solids.

This relationship between order and disorder is at the heart of Platonics. The collection seeks to show how they are not so far removed from one another ‚Äì and how we might embrace them both. It also aims to give collectors a behind the scenes look at how generative compositions can be constructed.

The geometric proof that there are only five convex regular polyhedra (the Platonic solids) states that at each vertex of the solid the angles between adjacent sides must be less than 360 degrees. This amount less than 360 degrees is known as the defect angle.

It is from this geometric proof that the collection size and pricing for Platonics is derived. There will be 360 Platonics sold via a Dutch auction priced according to the defect angles of the five Platonic solids: 180 > 120 > 90 > 60 > 36.

https://www.phaust.art/platonics

----------

Competition: Submit your favourite previews via Twitter to win a free mint and print.

Prints: Free gallery-grade, signed A3 prints for the first 18 mints.

Live: Press ‚ÄòS‚Äô to save in hi-res or append '&size=#' to the URL for custom height.

Info: Original artwork by Phaust. Winter 2023. London / Brighton. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Thirteen-576 #187
metadata.description:
We believe we have created a generative art piece which has the potential to be beautiful, to occasionally surprise and delight. To occasionally quieten the mind. We hope you enjoy it. 

Thirteen colours.
576 subtly different variations available via keyboard interaction.

1, 2 & 3 will change visible colour layers.
Q/q will switch between square and non-square layouts and toggle the border patterns on and off.
W/w will cycle between 3 border options.
E/e will cycle between 8 background options - if the default is no background then click E/e twice to activate.
R/r will cycle between 4 central motif rotation options. 
Most of these key presses will activate a complete redraw which may take a second or two for the more detailed patterns.

metadata.name: NOMADS #100
metadata.description:
NOMADS tells a story through each of its editions: the migration of a population, following simple rules, and whose movements reveal complex shapes and textures, both visual and auditory.
Movement, order, chaos, borders, convergence, wandering, rotation... it's all part of NOMADS

Enjoy the journey as much as the destination


KEYBOARD SHORCUTS:
[S]: Redraw the art and save a 4K PNG
[L]: Toggle between "Infinite Loop" and "Single Render" modes
[M]: Toggle mute

MOUSE / TOUCHSCREEN:
[Click / Tap]: Toggle mute
[Double Click / Double Tap]: Save the current render

URL PARAMETERS:
?start : bypass the intro timer and start the rendering
?loop : select the "Infinite Loop" mode by default
?resolution=1920x1080 : render in a custom resolution using the format WIDTHxHEIGHT. Different aspect ratios will produce different results.
?frame=0.1 : control the frame size around the canvas (value between 0 and 1)
?save : automatically save the image when the rendering is done


Artist: Estienne
Oct. 2022
NFT 2.0 License

Best viewed on Chrome or Chromium based browser
Tested on Chrome v 106.0.5249.119

Libraries used:
p5.js
Tone.js
A big 88 for randomly generated colors.

metadata.name: Painting Tiles #18
metadata.description:
The creation of this work was inspired by the tiling of the walls, the colors in 55 unique palettes are randomly selected by the machine and the movement of the colors in each tile is random.

What surprises the audience in this work is the simulation of a painter's behavior by a machine. 

All my efforts were to design effective algorithms to simulate the movement of colors on the canvas, the combination of colors and the random events that happen by an artist in his works, as if the produced work was made by human hands.

- Image Size 4000*4000 Pixels
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the current canvas.

Artist: Pointiago
Dec 22, 2022
License: NFT 2.0

By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel

2 - Toggle noise
3 - Toggle animation
4 - Randomize every 10 seconds

Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Each output consists of various geometric designs, displayed orthographically in rows, hopefully producing a pleasing result :)

Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.
